8. Why Reality Is More Complicated

Modern banking does not strictly follow this textbook model anymore.

Several factors matter:

1. Bank Capital Requirements

Banks must hold equity capital, not just reserves.

2. Loan Demand

Banks can only lend if people want loans.

3. Central Bank Policy

Central banks control interest rates and liquidity.

4. Risk Management

Banks limit lending if economic conditions are uncertain.

Because of these factors, modern economists often say:

Banks lend first and obtain reserves later.

9. Why This System Exists

Credit expansion allows economies to grow faster.

Businesses can:

borrow to invest

build factories

hire workers

expand production

Without credit creation, economic growth would be far slower.

10. The Hidden Risk

Credit expansion can also produce bubbles.

If banks create too much credit for assets like housing or stocks, prices can detach from reality.

This dynamic contributed heavily to the 2008 Financial Crisis.

When credit collapsed, large portions of the money supply effectively disappeared.

