The same system that enables growth also produces instability.

The cycle often looks like this:

1️⃣ Credit expands rapidly
2️⃣ Asset prices rise (housing, stocks)
3️⃣ Borrowing accelerates
4️⃣ Debt becomes excessive
5️⃣ Shock occurs
6️⃣ Credit collapses
7️⃣ Recession follows

The global banking crisis in the 2008 Financial Crisis followed this pattern.

Mortgage credit expanded rapidly, housing prices surged, and when loans defaulted the system froze.

6. Why Central Banks Exist

Central banks act as stabilizers in this system.

Their tools include:

interest rate policy

liquidity lending to banks

government bond purchases

emergency crisis interventions

Without central banks, banking panics would occur far more frequently.

