1. Why Governments Cannot Run Out of Their Own Currency

A government that issues its own sovereign currency can always create more of it.

For example, the United States government ultimately issues dollars through the monetary system coordinated with the Federal Reserve.

Because the state is the monopoly issuer of dollars, it cannot run out of them the way households or businesses can.

Households must earn or borrow money.

Governments that issue currency can create it.

This idea is emphasized in a school of thought called Modern Monetary Theory (MMT).

However, there is an important constraint.

The limit is inflation, not insolvency.

2. The Real Constraint: Resources

Money itself is just a financial tool.

The real economy consists of:

labor

energy

land

factories

technology

natural resources

If the government creates money faster than the economy can produce goods and services, prices rise.

This is why inflation occurs.

In extreme cases, it can lead to monetary collapse such as the Weimar Hyperinflation.

So the real constraint on money creation is:

the productive capacity of the economy.

