• Why inflation exists structurally

Inflation is often described as something caused by “printing too much money.”
But in modern economies inflation also exists for structural reasons built into how the system operates.

Think of inflation not as an accident but as a pressure that naturally emerges from several core features of modern economies.

1. Credit-Based Money Creation

Most money is created when banks issue loans.

Because loans carry interest, the system naturally pushes toward continuous credit expansion.

Example:

Loan created: $100

Repayment required: $105

For borrowers to collectively repay principal and interest, the economy must generate more money and income over time.

This encourages:

economic growth

credit expansion

gradual price increases

This dynamic became very visible leading up to the 2008 Financial Crisis when credit expansion inflated housing prices.

2. Growing Economies Require More Money

As economies expand, more money is needed to support:

more transactions

more businesses

more wages

more goods

If the money supply never increased, prices would tend to fall (deflation) as productivity rises.

Mild inflation helps keep the monetary system flexible.

Central banks such as the Federal Reserve therefore target about 2% inflation.

3. Wage Pressures

Workers naturally seek higher wages over time.

Businesses pass some of those higher costs into prices.

This process is sometimes called a wage–price dynamic.

It is especially visible in tight labor markets.

4. Government Fiscal Policy

Governments inject money through:

public spending

stimulus programs

infrastructure investment

If spending grows faster than production capacity, prices rise.

Large fiscal expansions during the COVID-19 Pandemic contributed to inflation in many countries.

5. Asset Inflation

Not all inflation appears in consumer prices.

A large portion occurs in assets, including:

housing

stocks

land

When credit flows heavily into these sectors, asset prices rise faster than incomes.

This type of inflation has been significant in many developed economies since the early 2000s.

6. Population Growth

More people means:

more consumption

more housing demand

more economic activity

That increases the need for money and production.

7. Monetary Policy Design

Central banks intentionally avoid zero inflation.

Why?

Because slight inflation helps prevent deflation, which can be economically dangerous.

Deflation encourages people to delay spending, slowing the economy.

For this reason institutions like the Federal Reserve intentionally target low but positive inflation.

8. Scarcity and Resource Limits

Real-world resources are limited.

When demand rises faster than supply, prices increase.

Examples include:

oil shocks

housing shortages

supply chain disruptions

These structural shortages produce inflation even without changes in money supply.

The Big Structural Insight

Modern economies are built around:

credit expansion

economic growth

controlled monetary flexibility

Because of this structure, some inflation is expected and even desired.

Zero inflation or falling prices would make the credit system unstable.

A Simple Way to Understand It

Inflation exists structurally because modern economies are designed to grow continuously.

Growth requires:

expanding credit

expanding money supply

rising wages and prices over time

So inflation is not only a policy failure.

It is also a built-in feature of the system.

